@NODE CONFIG_HELP_3 "DMC Configuration Help"

  The  next  line  on  your configuration file should (must) contain some
  text  which  will  be read/stored for the Title Heading shown atop each
  Index Page.

  It mustn't be longer than 30 chars maximum !!!

  These  can  be  in  either Upper or Lower case.    eg.    MY disk MaG !
  as  they  will  be  auto-converted to UPPERCASE anyway.    What's more,
  your message will now be auto-centred for you.    (Previous versions of
  DMC did not do this !)

  Another NEW feature:
  If  you type more than 30 chars, then I'm afraid that only the first 30
  will  be shown.    The code is now, erm, even more intelligent and will
  auto-matically round your text down to 30 chars if it exceeds the limit


                 * Please only use/type these chars: *

        ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ 0123456789 !"#&()*+,-./:<=>?'

  If  you  type  any others such as © then errors may occur.    I think I
  have included all the commonly used ones anyway !

  If you feel that you require more,  then you will have to purchase  the
  @{"SOURCE CODE" link SOURCE} from myself and update it.


  @{"CONFIGURATION" link CONFIGURATION}
  @{"CONFIG HELP 4" link CONFIG_HELP_4}
  @{" MAIN INDEX  " link MAIN}


@ENDNODE

@NODE CONFIG_HELP_4 "DMC Configuration Help"

  Each  INDEX  page can contain 20 articles, or to put it another way, 20
  lines  of  text displayed.    So if you had 22 Articles, then two Index
  Pages will be shown etc.

  As  a  pointer,  count the *'s that are down the left hand side of your
  config  file  and  this  will  tell you how many articles will be shown
  thus will tell you how many Inex Pages you will have

  eg.

  HELLO THERE MY FRIENDS
  *empty*
  HOW THE DEVIL ARE YOU ?
  *empty*
  CLICK ON ME TO LOAD SOME TEXT
  *dox*YourDisk:YourDir/YourFile
  CLICK ON ME TO LOAD A PICCY
  *iff*YourDisk:YourDir/YourFile

  The above will only use 4 lines on the Index page. (count the *'s down
  the left hand side)

  You MUST follow your text with *empty*  *iff*  or  *dox*

  If you follow the text with *empty* then it cannot be selected with the
  mouse.    If you follow it with either *iff* or *dox* then the text can
  be selected and it will try to load either an iff piccy or a text file.

  Always follow either *dox* or *iff* with the correct path of your files

  I  have  included an ErrorTrap in the code just in case the file cannot
  be found.    Always check for spelling mistakes etc.    just in case.

  (A  couple  of  Registered users sent me their corrupt config files and
  they  had BLANK lines instead of *empty* and sometimes even *empty* was
  spelt wrongly !!!    - So be careful and check everything)

  Another point, ALWAYS press RETURN after EACH line !!!

  Most  text  editors  will  have  a  function to let you see on screen a
  symbol  to  show End Of Lines.    (EOL'S - usually an arrow shaped like
  RETURN  key)  This is sometimes called RETURNS on text editors.    Just
  the same thing !

  I  can't  think how anyone could type on the next line without pressing
  RETURN  first  anyway !    However, no doubt I will be proved wrong, so
  make sure you do it as my code looks for the RETURN CHAR (Char$(10)) at
  the end of each line.

  Do NOT leave blank lines in your file.    Always type *empty* to create
  a blank line to be displayed on screen.

  When  you have finally finished typing your file and checked it for any
  spelling mistakes etc.    Save it to disk as DMC.Config


  Have  a look at the one on this disk if you are still unsure as to what
  it  should look like.    Above all, persevere and you will get to grips
  with  it  within  a  few hours I'm sure.    It's not complicated if you
  study it for a short while.  Honest !  :)


  @{"CONFIGURATION" link CONFIGURATION}
  @{" MAIN INDEX  " link MAIN}


@ENDNODE

@NODE ARTICLES "DMC Creating Articles"

  CREATING AN ARTICLE:
  ~~~~~~~~ ~~ ~~~~~~~~

  Your  articles  must  be  typed and saved as a normal ASCII text files.
  Most  text editors save in this format so there shouldn't be a problem.
  
  Each  article  when  displayed  on screen will be shown as 24 lines per
  page.

  An  article  with  Up to 200 pages can be shown !    So that means that
  you  musn't  type more than 4800 lines of text.    phew !    That works
  out at 200 pages * 24 lines of text = 4800 lines.

  Your articles can include coloured text and every  character could be a
  different colour if you wanted it to be !    A maximum of seven colours
  can be shown.

  1-White (default)
  2-red
  3-yellow
  4-green
  5-cyan
  6-blue
  7-purple (flashing)

  To create a line of text in red you would do this;


  Press  Shift  and  # which will display a @ symbol.    Follow this by a
  number  ranging from 1-7 (we'll use 2 for red).    Do not leave a space
  between the @ and number.

  Now type your text and it will be shown on screen as red coloured text.

  eg. @2This line has red text.
      @7This line has purple flashing text.
      @1WHITE @2RED @3YELLOW @4GREEN @5CYAN @6BLUE @7PURPLE

  Load  any of the articles on this disk into your text editor to see how
  it's done.

  Please note that DMC now supports  @{"SPLIT SCREEN" link SPLIT} articles and there are
  full instructions on this disk on how to create them with ease.

  Also NEW to this version of DMC is the @{"SECRET" link SECRET} articles.


  @{"MAIN INDEX" link MAIN}


@ENDNODE

@NODE SPLIT "DMC Split Screen/Two Column Articles"

  Split Screen Articles (aka two column mode):
  ~~~~~ ~~~~~~ ~~~~~~~~ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  DMC  now allows Split-Screen text articles as well as normal text arts.

  Probably  better  known  as two column articles like those used in that
  very popular disk mag ... Grapevine and now in Amoszine.

  Basically they look like this on screen:

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------



                                 BIG TOP HEADING

                                 Smaller Heading

Hello there my friends. How the devil  It reads all the questions and music
are you ? I thought I would right and  files from a data disk and therefore
let you know of my latest production   any future data disks will bring a
that I have been busy with.            whole new game !  I have included a
                                       whost of utilities that will let you
It's called The Ultimate Quiz Vol.#2   create your very own data disks with
                                       ease.
It comes on two disks and is available Just released are two NEW data disks
via F1 Licenecware for only Ł4.99.     for use with the game also.


(up to 24 lines shown on screen)       (up to 24 lines shown on screen)


  -------------------------------------------------------------------------


  The above is just a short example of a two-colum (split screen) article
  to give you some idea of what they will look like.

  You can either type them up yourself in this fashion or use the @{"TESTER" link TESTER}
  to convert a normal text file into the above format easily.


  Some quick instructions about split-screen articles:


  The very first thing that you need to type is <> as this will allow the
  code  to  set  it's  default  text  reader  to use the new Split-Screen
  option.

  If you want a heading at the top of the page, you must type  { followed
  by your heading.  (This will be auto-centred for you).

  eg.  {TOP BIG HEADING

  You may also like to add a title for the name of the author. To do this
  you simply type  } before the text. (This will be auto-centred)

  eg.  }BOTTOM SMALLER HEADING

  Now you need to type up the rest of the article.


  Please note that no more than 38 chars should be typed per line.
  That does not include the colour codes ...

  Again, 7 colours can be used and these are:

  White Red Yellow Green Cyan Blue and of course Purple (flashing)


  To  add any of the above colours to your text, just put the @ character
  followed by a number from 1 to 7.

  eg. @1Would give White text.
      @4Would give Green text.

  As  mentioned before, only type a maximum of 38 chars per line.    Then
  you can add in all your colour codes later (Only up to 79 chars on each
  line).

  eg.

  THIS LINE HAS USED UP THE 38 CHARS !!!

  @1THIS @2LINE @3HAS @4USED @5UP @6THE @138 @2CHARS @3!@4!@5!

  (Even although the above line is only 38 chars long, it has used up 61
  char spaces due to the colour codes being added !)

  Up to 24 lines of text can be shown on each screen.

  Use the new @{"TESTER" link TESTER} to see how your articles look before you use them
  in your final production.

  The  best  way  to learn is by loading the files on this disk into your
  text  editor  and  messing about with them.    Above all, make sure you
  don't give up as it is all pretty straight forward.

